This is a very opinionated and speculative interpretation of a very general
statement:

&quot;ICV2 is reporting that according to a notice sent to retailers, ADV Films
will be handling the marketing, sales, and distribution for Geneon's entire
catalog beginning October 1. The notice mentioned that Geneon will still be
licensing and producing anime for North America, but the way those titles
reach the market will now be handled by ADV Films. ADV Films declined to
comment for this article; Geneon could not be reached for comment.&quot;

These are the inaccuracies in the conclusions you drew from this general
statement:

- Geneon is not a minor company - they are right behind ADV and Viz in
number of titles.  Since you use Anime News Network as a source, you might
want to check their Geneon listings:
http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/encyclopedia/company.php?id=1782

- Geneon is neither folding or being absorbed.  They are outsourcing
certain activities.

-  You may not be able to see how Geneon will be able to &quot;continue to
license and produce anime.&quot;  Nevetheless, the notice that went out to
retailers specifically said, &quot;This change will in no way impact the
availability of current or future Geneon titles 'in the pipeline.'&quot;

The last quote came from the source article that you should have referred
to before you started reading in between the lines.  It's available at:

http://www.icv2.com/articles/home/11182.html

These are the concluding two paragraphs that were not included in the Anime
News Network blurb:

&quot;The extensive Geneon catalogue will continue to be available through ADV,
making a formidable combined title roster from the two companies.

&quot;The business impacts at both companies seem positive (although there are
displaced Geneon employees who do not share in the benefits).  Geneon rids
itself of a sales, marketing, and distribution function that is servicing
much lower volume than it did in the days when Geneon was distributing Viz
(Pokemon) and Bandai titles.  ADV gains the economies of scale of servicing
larger volume on a similar expense base.&quot;

Bottom Line:  It sounds like a good business arrangement by two major North
American anime companies.  It looks like the consumer will benefit.  The
only downside would be if you are a Geneon employee of one of the areas
that is to be outsourced.

Mata ato de,

Phil Yff
